Small slip up from my previous PR.
For our use-case of deny link::mask it really makes more sense to deny linking when no masks match.
Take this block for example:
deny link {
	mask {
		!foobar.hub;
                !somethingelse.hub;
	};
	rule !connected(foobar.hub)&&!connected(somethingelse.hub);
	type all;
};

would end up denying all links because you can't match foobar.hub and somethingelse.hub at the same time. This is fixed by having the function return 0 on the first non-match

